all [List.get]\n                                <;>\n                                  (try omega)\n                              exact h₂₅\n                            rw [h₂₀, h₂₃]\n                          exact h₁₃\n                      exact h₉\n                    exact h₈ i hi\n                  exact h₇\n                exact h₆\n              exact h₃\n            rw [h₂]\n            <;> simp\n    linarith\n  have h₂ := h l\n  simp only [smaller, larger] at h₂ ⊢\n  linarith",
      "\n   Actually, no: `List.count_filter` doesn't seem relevant because it states `(l.filter p).count x = l.count x` if `p x` is true. That's not useful for our problem.\n\nAlternatively, perhaps:\n- For any `l`, we have `l = (l.filter p) ++ (l.filter (¬ p ·))` where `p` is a predicate. But no, not quite because some elements may not satisfy `p` nor `¬ p` if the predicate is not decidable (but in Lean it is). Wait, no, assuming we have excluded middle, `p x ∨ ¬ p x`.\n\nBut in our case, the two filters are `≤ pivot` and `> pivot`. For any element, it is in exactly one of these two, because either `x ≤ pivot` or `x > pivot`, but not both.\n\nSo:\n`l = (l.filter (· ≤ pivot)) ++ (l.filter (· > pivot))`? \nNo, because the order is not preserved unless we do something else. But for counts, it doesn't matter, because count is order-independent:\n`l.count x = (l.filter (· ≤ pivot)).count x + (l.filter (· > pivot)).count x`.\n\nBecause every occurrence of `x` is in exactly one of the two filtered lists (since `x ≤ pivot` or `x > pivot`).\n\nBut in Lean, `smaller pivot l = l.filter (· ≤ pivot)` and `larger pivot l = l.filter (· > pivot)`.\n\nThus, it follows that `l.count x = (smaller pivot l).count x + (larger pivot l).count x`.\n\nBut to prove it formally, we can use that:\n`(p : α → Prop) → l.count x = (l.filter p).count x + (l.filter (¬ p ·)).count x`, provided that `p x` is decidable. But perhaps Lean's library has this?\n\nActually, no, not directly. However, perhaps it's better to use that:\nEvery element is in either `smaller` or `larger`, but not both, and so their counts add up.\n\nBut another approach is to prove that:\n`(l.filter p).count x + (l.filter q).count x = l.count x`, if `p` and `q` are complementary and disjoint (but in fact, for count, we only need that every occurrence is in exactly one of the two).\n\nHowever, it seems that Lean might not have a general lemma for that. \n\nAn alternative is to prove that `(smaller pivot l) ++ (larger pivot l)` is a permutation of `l`, but we don't need that for count, because count is permutation-invariant.\n\nBut perhaps the `List.count_filter` lemma can help when the element satisfies the predicate. \n\nBut perhaps we can prove it by induction on `l`.\n\n### Step 3: Proof Sketch\n\nWe'll prove it by induction on `l`.\n\n**Base Case: `l = []`.**\n- `smaller pivot [] = []`, `larger pivot [] = []`.\n- Then `[].count x = 0`, and `[] + [] = 0`.\n\n**Inductive Step:**\nAssume it is true for `l`, prove it for `a :: l`.\n\nWe need to consider `(a :: l).count x`, which is `if a = x then 1 else 0 + l.count x`.\n\nThen, `(smaller pivot (a :: l)) = if a ≤ pivot then a :: smaller pivot l else smaller pivot l`,\nand similarly for `larger`.\n\nThus, we need to break into cases:\n1. `a = x`.\n2. `a ≠ x`.\n\nBut perhaps better to break into:",
      "\n  have h_main : l.count x = (l.filter (fun y => y ≤ pivot)).count x + (l.filter (fun y => pivot < y)).count x := by\n    have h₁ : l.count x = (l.filter (fun y => y ≤ pivot) ++ l.filter (fun y => pivot < y)).count x := by\n      have h₂ : l.filter (fun y => y ≤ pivot) ++ l.filter (fun y => pivot < y) = l := by\n        apply List.ext_get\n        intro i hi\n        have h₃ : l.get ⟨i, hi⟩ = l.get ⟨i, hi⟩ := rfl\n        by_cases h₄ : l.get ⟨i, hi⟩ ≤ pivot <;> by_cases h₅ : pivot < l.get ⟨i, hi⟩ <;> simp_all [List.get, List.filter, List.append_get]\n        <;>\n        (try omega) <;>\n        (try {\n          exfalso\n          have h₆ := le_total (l.get ⟨i, hi⟩) pivot\n          simp_all\n          <;>\n          omega\n        })\n      rw [h₂]\n    rw [h₁]\n    have h₃ : Disjoint (l.filter (fun y => y ≤ pivot)) (l.filter (fun y => pivot < y)) := by\n      apply List.disjoint_left.mpr\n      intro a ha₁ ha₂\n      simp [List.mem_filter] at ha₁ ha₂\n      have h₄ : a ≤ pivot := ha₁.2\n      have h₅ : pivot < a := ha₂.2\n      have h₆ : ¬(a ≤ pivot ∧ pivot < a) := by\n        intro h\n        have h₇ : a ≤ pivot := h.1\n        have h₈ : pivot < a := h.2\n        have h₉ : a < a := by\n          calc\n            a ≤ pivot := h₇\n            _ < a := h₈\n        exact lt_irrefl a h₉\n      exact h₆ ⟨h₄, h₅⟩\n    rw [List.count_append]\n    <;> simp_all [Disjoint]\n    <;>\n    (try simp_all) <;>\n    (try omega)\n  \n  have h_final : (l.count x) = (smaller pivot l).count x + (larger pivot l).count x := by\n    have h₁ : (smaller pivot l).count x = (l.filter (fun y => y ≤ pivot)).count x := by\n      rfl\n    have h₂ : (larger pivot l).count x = (l.filter (fun y => pivot < y)).count x := by\n      rfl\n    have h₃ : l.count x = (l.filter (fun y => y ≤ pivot)).count x + (l.filter (fun y => pivot < y)).count x := h_main\n    linarith\n  \n  apply h_final"
